    <text>
        <front/>
        <body>
            <pb n="3" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">To the EDITOR of the MORNING CHRONICLE.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <opener>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">SIR,</hi>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>To prove how circumspect travellers ought to be in<lb break="yes"/>the explanation of hieroglyphic characters found among<lb break="yes"/>half civilised people, I have referred, in my <hi rendition="#i">Researches<lb break="yes"/>on the Monuments of the New Continent, page</hi> 62,<lb break="yes"/>to a fact observed among the Betjuans of Southern<lb break="yes"/>Africa. A traveller had seen children etching on a<lb break="yes"/>rock certain characters accidentally resembling the let-<lb break="no"/>ters P and M of the Roman alphabet. This observa-<lb break="no" />tion I have attributed to Mr. Trüter, and I have quoted<lb break="yes"/>the work from which it was taken&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">The Geographical<lb break="yes"/>Ephemerides of Mr. <choice><sic>Bostuch</sic><corr type="editorial">Bertuch</corr></choice>.</hi> This fact, however,<lb break="yes"/>has exposed me to a severe criticism in the twenty-sixth<lb break="yes"/>number of the <hi rendition="#i">Quarterly Review.</hi> In the analysis of<lb break="yes"/>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Campbell’s Missionary Travels</hi> it is affirmed, that no<lb break="yes"/>such circumstance is related in Mr. Trüter’s work, nor<lb break="yes"/>even any allusion of the kind; and after commencing<lb break="yes"/>with these words. “<hi rendition="#i">If any credit were due to the au-<lb break="no"/>thority of Mr. Humboldt,</hi>” the article terminates with<lb break="yes"/>the following, “<hi rendition="#i">yet this is a fact on which Mr. Hum-<lb break="no"/>boldt hangs one of his numerous theories.</hi>”</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>I do not pretend that my name is of great authority<lb break="yes"/>concerning facts not examined with my own eye. Few<lb break="yes"/>authors are more sensible of the imperfections of their<lb break="yes"/>own works than I am; but I believe that in what re-<lb break="no"/>lates to the Betjuanas, the fault is not so great as this<lb break="yes"/>unfriendly critic would imagine. The fact in question,<lb break="yes"/>contained in the <hi rendition="#i">Ephemerides of Mr. <choice><sic>Bostuch</sic><corr type="editorial">Bertuch</corr></choice>, of May</hi>
                    <lb break="yes"/>1807, <hi rendition="#i">p.</hi> 32. <hi rendition="#i">l.</hi> 25. is thus related:&#x2014;“Among the<lb break="yes"/>Betjuanas’ children of ten or twelve years of age, were<lb break="yes"/>occupied in engraving figures upon a rock with a pointed<lb break="yes"/>instrument, some of which so much resembled the M,<lb break="yes"/>H, and P of the Roman alphabet, that travellers might<lb break="yes"/>mistake them for true letters.” This circumstance was<lb break="yes"/>noticed by me not for the purpose of establishing, but<lb break="yes"/>of condemning, theories, and particularly to prove, that<lb break="yes"/>a resemblance of Phœnician characters, with some signs<lb break="yes"/>traced on the rocks of the Orinoco, is merely accidental.<lb break="yes"/>I was only deceived in referring, as authority in this<lb break="yes"/>case, to Mr. Trüter, a name perfectly well known to<lb break="yes"/>me by the excellent <hi rendition="#i">Travels of Mr. Barrow.</hi> The<lb break="yes"/>observation, however, is that of Dr. Lichtenstein, sent<lb break="yes"/>by General Jansen, in 1803, to the country of the Bet-<lb break="no"/>juanas, and whose report is inserted in the <hi rendition="#i">Ephemerides<lb break="yes"/>of Mr. <choice><sic>Bostuch</sic><corr type="editorial">Bertuch</corr></choice>.</hi> As Dr. Lichtenstein often compares<lb break="yes"/>his observations with those of Mr. Trüter, it so hap-<lb break="no"/>pened that I confounded the two travellers who had<lb break="yes"/>visited the same nation and examined the same objects.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">ALEXANDER HUMBOLDT, F.R.S.</hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <dateline>Paris, Jan. 24, 1816.</dateline>
            </div>
